      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "When sentences spiral outwards, use ellipses in your scratch work to show skipped clauses, only fully diagramming the critical pivot points. Think visually of deep trees like a large gathering of root systems; trace the *main* roots (the head words) first before following the distracting side-shoots of modifiers. Also, build your sentences piece by piece, grafting phrases onto existing nodes rather than trying to diagram the whole complex structure at once. This piecemeal approach keeps localized modules manageable as the whole sentence grows more elaborate.",
      "source": "target",
